    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-23\">\n<h2>6-23</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 5: Linear Modeling with Data</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Develops upper and lower bounds around a linear model using maximum residuals to describe prediction variability.</div>\n<div><p>Because the height you found for the humanoid is a prediction, the actual height of the early humanoid was probably a little shorter or a little taller.  In this problem, you will investigate how you can report a <em>range</em> of values for your prediction of the humanoid’s height. \t</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Look at the data you collected and the line that models the data.  Identify the point that is farthest from the line you drew.  Calculate the residual for this point. </p></li><li><p>In a different color, draw a dashed line that goes through this maximum residual point and is parallel to the line of your model.  An example is shown below.  Then draw another dashed line that is on the other side of your model and is the same distance away as the first dashed line.  You have just drawn the upper and lower bounds for the variability of the data.  \t\t</p><p><img alt=\"Your teacher will provide you with a model of the graph.\" class=\"figure-img\" src=\"assets/6-23.png\"/></p></li><li><p>Using the upper and lower bounds that you just drew, create a range of values for the possible height of a humanoid with a forearm length of $26.4$ cm. </p></li><li><p>With your team, discuss the bounds of the data.  Was your model useful for predicting the height of the humanoid?</p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
