    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-33\">\n<h2>6-33</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 5: Linear Modeling with Data</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses the least squares regression line to model data, analyze residuals, predict, and interpret slope and intercept.</div>\n<div><p>A least squares regression line (LSRL) is a unique line that has the smallest possible value for the sum of the squares of the residuals. \t</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Your teacher will show you how to use your calculator to make a scatterplot or use the <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/kcpzeeyt3d\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">6-33 Student eTool</a>. (Hand-held graphing calculator instructions can also be downloaded <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"http://pdfs.cpm.org/standards/stats/Stats_Appendix_TI_Calc.pdf\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">TI Calculator Instructions</a>.) Be sure to use the checksum at the bottom of the table in problem 6-30 to verify that you entered the data into your calculator accurately. Click in the lower right corner of the graph to view it in full-screen mode.  \t\t</p><img alt=\"Graph for 6-33\" class=\"figure-img\" src=\"assets/6-33.png\"/></li><li><p>Your teacher will show you how to find the LSRL and graph it on your calculator. Sketch your scatterplot and LSRL on your paper. </p></li><li><p>Your teacher will show you how to find the residuals for the LSRL using your calculator. What is the sum of the squares of the residuals of the LSRL the calculator found? Was it less than your sum of squares? </p></li><li><p>How many points does the LSRL predict for Antonio Kusoc? </p></li><li><p>Interpret the slope and <em>y</em>-intercept of the model in context. Explain why this LSRL model is not reasonable for players that played less than about 350 minutes.  </p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
