    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-34\">\n<h2>6-34</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 5: Linear Modeling with Data</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Investigates least squares regression by minimizing residual sums and squared residual sums using a graphing tool.</div>\n<div><p> Investigate the LSRL and minimizing the squares of the residuals using a computer. Go to the <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/e5titkgc8s\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">6-34 Student eTool</a>. Click in the lower right corner of the graph to view it in full-screen mode.  \t</p><img alt=\"Graph for 6-34\" class=\"figure-img\" src=\"assets/6-34.png\"/><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Position the line so that you think it best fits the data.</p></li><li><p>Show the residuals and their sum.  Now drag the line to reduce the sum of residuals. What is the lowest sum of residuals you can get?   </p></li><li><p>Since there is sometimes more than one line that has the least sum of residuals, mathematicians minimize the sum of the squares of the residuals instead. Show the squares and the squares sum, but hide the residuals, and the residuals sum. Drag the line to make the squares as small as possible and reduce the sum of squares residuals. What is the lowest sum of squares you can get? </p></li><li><p>Now show the LSRL. There is only one LSRL that minimizes the sum of the squares. All other lines have a larger sum of squares. How close did you get?</p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
