    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-49\">\n<h2>6-49</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 5: Linear Modeling with Data</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Matches scatterplots to residual plots and uses residual-plot patterns to judge whether a linear model fits.</div>\n<div><p>A<strong> residual plot</strong> can help you determine if a linear model is a good fit for a scatterplot of data. Whenever a LSRL is drawn on a scatterplot, a residual plot can also be created.  A residual plot has an <em>$x$</em>-axis that is the same as the scatterplot, and a <em>$y$</em>-axis that plots the residual. \t</p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Match each scatterplot below with its corresponding residual plot. </p><div class=\"row\"><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p>Scatterplot I</p></div><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p>Scatterplot II</p></div><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p>Scatterplot III</p></div></div><div class=\"row\"><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p>Residual Plot A</p></div><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p>Residual Plot B</p></div><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p>Residual Plot C</p></div></div></li><li><p>For which of the scatterplots does a linear model fit the data best? How does the residual plot help you make that decision? </p></li></ol></div>\n<div class=\"captured-figures\"><figure><img alt=\"Captured figure for 6-49\" class=\"figure-img\" src=\"assets/6-49.png\"/><figcaption>Captured figure for 6-49</figcaption></figure></div>\n</section>",
