    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-51\">\n<h2>6-51</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 5: Linear Modeling with Data</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses a residual plot to test whether a linear model is appropriate and to infer the shape of the original data.</div>\n<div><div class=\"row\"><div class=\"col-sm-9\"><p>Dry ice (frozen carbon dioxide) has the unusual property of sublimating (changing directly from a solid to a gas). Giulia’s father uses dry ice to keep the glasses in the restaurant cold. Since dry ice sublimates in the restaurant cooler, Giulia was curious how long a piece of dry ice would last.<br/>She collected the following data:</p><table><tbody><tr><th><p># of hours after noon</p></th><th><p>Weight of dry ice (oz)</p></th></tr><tr><td><p>$0$</p></td><td><p>$15.3$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$1$</p></td><td><p>$14.7$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$2$</p></td><td><p>$14.3$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$3$</p></td><td><p>$13.6$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$4$</p></td><td><p>$13.1$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$5$</p></td><td><p>$12.5$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$6$</p></td><td><p>$11.9$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$7$</p></td><td><p>$11.5$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$8$</p></td><td><p>$11.0$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$9$</p></td><td><p>$10.6$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$10$</p></td><td><p>$10.2$</p></td></tr></tbody></table><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Sketch the scatterplot and LSRL of this data.  </p></li><li><p>Use your calculator or <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/x0pclatfjn\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">6-51 Student eTool</a> to make a residual plot to determine if a linear model is appropriate. Make a conjecture about what the residual plot tells you about the shape of the original data Giulia collected. Click in the lower right corner of the graph to view it in full-screen mode. </p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"captured-figures\"><figure><img alt=\"Captured figure for 6-51\" class=\"figure-img\" src=\"assets/6-51.png\"/><figcaption>Captured figure for 6-51</figcaption></figure></div>\n</section>",
