    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-72\">\n<h2>6-72</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 5: Linear Modeling with Data</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Extension using scatterplots to connect correlation, slope, and point influence.</div>\n<div><p><strong>Extension: </strong>A computer will help us explore the correlation coefficient further. Go to <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/wj4nclf18y\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">6-72 Student eTool</a>. Click in the lower right corner of the graph to view it in full-screen mode. </p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Create scatterplots with the following associations and record <em>r</em>: </p><ul class=\"bullet\"><li><p>Strong positive linear association</p></li><li><p>Weak positive linear association</p></li><li><p>Strong negative linear association</p></li><li><p>No linear association (random scatter)</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Create a scatterplot with a strong negative linear association such that <em>$r \\lt -0.95$</em>. Drag one of the points around to observe the effect on the slope and correlation coefficient. Can you make the slope positive by dragging just one point? </p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
