    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-81\">\n<h2>6-81</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 5: Linear Modeling with Data</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Evaluates a causal claim from an observational study and proposes alternative explanations for an association.</div>\n<div><div class=\"row\"><div class=\"col-sm-9\"><p>A dietician studying the benefits of eating spinach surveyed a large sample of individuals. She recorded the amount of spinach they ate and their physical strength. The dietician found the spinach eaters to be much stronger than the non-spinach eaters. The next day the newspaper headline was, <em>“Popeye was right! Eating spinach makes you stronger!”</em></p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Do you agree with the newspaper? Do you agree that if you eat more spinach, you will grow stronger muscles and increase your strength?  </p></li><li><p>The dietician correctly found an association. What could explain this association other than spinach makes you stronger? </p></li></ol></div></div></div>\n</section>",
