    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-86\">\n<h2>6-86</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 2, Section 5: Linear Modeling with Data</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Interprets slope, residuals, boundary lines, and model reliability in an amusement-park attendance context.</div>\n<div><p>Marissa went with her friends to the amusement park on a beautiful spring day. The park was crowded. Marissa wondered if there was an association between the weather and attendance. From data she received at the theme park office, Marissa randomly picked ten Saturdays and analyzed the data. </p><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Marissa calculated the least squares regression line <em>$a = -14 + 0.41t,$</em> where <em>a</em> is the attendance (in $1000\\text{s}$) and <em>t</em> is the high temperature ($^\\circ \\text{F}$) that day. Interpret the slope in this context.</p></li></ol><div class=\"row\"><div class=\"col-xl-8\"><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\"><li><p>The residual plot Marissa created is shown at right. On days when temperatures were in the $80\\text{s}$, would you expect the predictions made by Marissa’s model to be too high, too low, or pretty accurate?</p></li></ol></div><div class=\"col-xl-4 col-align-top\"><p><img alt=\"Figure for 6-86\" class=\"figure-img\" src=\"assets/6-86.png\"/></p></div></div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"3\" type=\"a\"><li><p>What was the actual attendance on the day when the temperature was $95^\\circ \\text{F}$?</p></li><li><p>Marissa drew the upper boundary line at <em>$a = -7 + 0.41t$ </em>and the lower boundary line at <em>$a = -21 + 0.41t$</em>. What are the upper and lower bounds for the predicted number of people attending when the temperature is $80^\\circ \\text{F}$?</p></li><li><p>Would you rely on this model to make predictions? Why or why not?</p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
