    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"9-54\">\n<h2>9-54</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 6, Section 5: Quadratic Modeling</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses a quadratic model for a rocket path to find and interpret x-intercepts; keeps the useful HW eTool link.</div>\n<div><p>Robbie builds model rockets. One day he sets up a rocket, backs away from the launch pad, and then shoots the rocket off into the air. The rocket's path is represented by the equation $y=-10x^2+130x-400$, where $y$ is the height in meters off the ground and $x$ is the horizontal distance in meters from Robbie. <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/so8j2svnvz\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">9-54 HW eTool</a></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li><p>Use either the Zero Product Property or the Quadratic Formula to find the $x$-intercepts of the path of Robbie's rocket. What do the $x$-intercepts tell you?</p></li>\n<li><p>When Robbie's rocket lands, how far is it from the launch pad?</p></li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>",
