    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-2\">\n<h2>10-2</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Statistics and Probability / Two-Way Tables and Association</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Introduces two-way tables as an organized alternative to Venn diagrams and asks for probabilities from the completed table.</div>\n<div>\n<p>Raul said he could not figure out how to put the data from problem 10-1 into a Venn diagram because it was hard to find the number of students with both $\\pi$Phones and laptops, so he put the information into a table like the one below.</p>\n<p class=\"center\"><img alt=\"Problem visual for 10-2.png\" class=\"figure\" src=\"assets/10-2.png\" style=\"max-width:520px;\"/></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Copy and complete Raul’s table to figure out the number of students in the missing cells.</li>\n<li>This type of table is called a <strong>two-way table</strong> and is often used to organize information and calculate probabilities. How is it similar to and different from a Venn diagram? What are its advantages or disadvantages?</li>\n<li>If we assume that Pham’s survey is from a random sample of students in his school:\n<ol class=\"lower-roman\" type=\"i\">\n<li>What is the probability that a student at his high school has a $\\pi$Phone <em>or</em> a laptop?</li>\n<li>What is the probability that a student has a $\\pi$Phone <em>and</em> a laptop?</li>\n</ol></li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</section>",
