    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-6\">\n<h2>10-6</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Statistics and Probability / Two-Way Tables and Association</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses a large two-way table to compute probabilities involving living arrangement and age groups; keeps the resource-page link.</div>\n<div>\n<p>According to the U.S. Census Bureau, of the $312.59$ million people living in the U.S. in 2011, the number of people living alone is given in the two-way table below (in millions). Obtain the <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"http://pdfs.cpm.org/stuRes/CCA/chapter_10/CCA%20Lesson%2010.1.1%20RP.pdf\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">Lesson 10.1.1 Resource Page</a> for a copy of this table that you can write on.</p>\n<p class=\"center\"><strong># people (in millions)</strong></p>\n<table class=\"data-table\"><tr><th>Age</th><th>Under 25</th><th>25 to 34</th><th>35 to 44</th><th>45 to 54</th><th>55 to 64</th><th>65 to 74</th><th>75 or Over</th></tr>\n<tr><th>Living alone</th><td>1.45</td><td>4.16</td><td>3.55</td><td>5.57</td><td>6.69</td><td>4.81</td><td>6.50</td></tr>\n<tr><th>Living with others</th><td>109.67</td><td>37.41</td><td>36.28</td><td>38.37</td><td>30.28</td><td>16.59</td><td>11.26</td></tr></table>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Why do you think this is called a two-way table?</li>\n<li>What is the probability of living alone?</li>\n<li>What is the probability of being $65$ or over?</li>\n<li>What is the probability of being under $65$?</li>\n<li>What is the probability of being under 35 years of age <em>and</em> living alone?</li>\n<li>To find the probability of being under 35 years of age <em>or</em> living alone, Qui added the total number of people in the first two columns to the total number of people in the first row. What did Qui do wrong?</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</section>",
