    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"10-9\">\n<h2>10-9</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Statistics and Probability / Two-Way Tables and Association</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Explores association through conditional relative frequency tables under different choices of independent variable.</div>\n<div>\n<p>Is there an association between chores and curfews? In other words, do students who do more chores also have a stricter curfew?</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>The data for 27 students in the two-way table below is fabricated (“made up”) to make a point. Assume that curfew is the independent variable. That means that you should find the total number of students having early curfew or late curfew when you create a conditional relative frequency table. Then the columns of “curfew” will add up to $100\\%$.</li>\n</ol>\n<p class=\"center\"><img alt=\"Problem visual for 10-9a.png\" class=\"figure\" src=\"assets/10-9a.png\" style=\"max-width:420px;\"/></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"2\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Is there an association between chores and curfew? Explain based on the conditional relative frequency table you made.</li>\n<li>Does doing chores depend on whether you have an early or late curfew, or does having an early or late curfew depend on whether you do chores or not? Does it matter? This time, assume that chores is the independent variable. Make a new conditional relative frequency table by finding the totals of doing or not doing chores. Since chores is the independent variable, interchange the rows and columns.</li>\n</ol>\n<p class=\"center\"><img alt=\"Problem visual for 10-9c.png\" class=\"figure\" src=\"assets/10-9c.png\" style=\"max-width:420px;\"/></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"4\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Now consider this new group of 27 fabricated students. Is there an association if curfew is the independent variable? Is there an association if chores is the independent variable? Make conditional relative frequency tables for both situations.</li>\n</ol>\n<p class=\"center\"><img alt=\"Problem visual for 10-9d.png\" class=\"figure\" src=\"assets/10-9d.png\" style=\"max-width:420px;\"/></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" start=\"5\" type=\"a\"><li>What is interesting about the conditional relative frequency tables that have no association?</li></ol>\n</div>\n</section>",
