    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-44\">\n<h2>11-44</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Statistics and Probability / One-Variable Data Displays and Summary Statistics</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Introduces center, shape, spread, and outliers as a framework for comparing single-variable data distributions.</div>\n<p><strong>Center, Shape, Spread, and Outliers</strong></p>\n<p>When you described the relationship between two variables on a scatterplot in Chapter 6, it took several statistics to get a meaningful description of the data: form, direction, strength, and outliers.</p>\n<p>Similarly, it takes several statistics to get a meaningful description of single-variable data like the sales prices of houses in Fancyville and Smallville—comparing the medians alone did not tell a useful story about the difference in prices. Statisticians like to report the <strong>center</strong>, <strong>shape</strong>, <strong>spread</strong>, and <strong>outliers</strong> of single-variable data.</p>\n<p>Your teacher will give you the data from a previous “Forty Holes of Golf” fundraiser on the <a class=\"resource\" href=\"http://pdfs.cpm.org/stuRes/CCA/chapter_11/CCA%20Lesson%2011.2.2B%20RP.pdf\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Lesson 11.2.2B Resource Page</a>. Compare the center, shape, spread, and outliers of your team's performance to the previous team's.</p>\n</section>",
