    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-60\">\n<h2>11-60</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Statistics and Probability / One-Variable Data Displays and Summary Statistics</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Compares two one-variable data sets using graphs, mean, median, and spread to decide which sugar consistently produces larger cells.</div>\n<p>A biologist is trying to determine which sugar is more successful in growing a particular eukaryotic cell. She collected the data below, diameter in micrometers.</p>\n<p><strong>Sugar W:</strong> $10, 32, 32, 34, 34, 36, 37, 39, 39, 40, 41, 43, 43, 44, 45, 46, 46, 49, 70$ <br/><em>checksum</em> $760$</p>\n<p><strong>Sugar P:</strong> $10, 10, 15, 20, 25, 28, 30, 32, 35, 40, 45, 48, 50, 52, 55, 60, 65, 70, 70$ <br/><em>checksum</em> $760$</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>Make a combination histogram and boxplot for each sugar. Use an interval of $10$ to $80$ with a bin width of $10$.</li><li>Find the mean and median of both collections of data.</li><li>The two sets of data are obviously not the same. Which statistic(s) differentiate between these two data sets? You do not need to calculate the statistic. If the biologist wants to consistently grow large cells, which sugar should she use?</li></ol>\n</section>",
