    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-61\">\n<h2>11-61</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Statistics and Probability / One-Variable Data Displays and Summary Statistics</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Develops measures of spread including range, mean absolute deviation, and IQR, with attention to outliers and symmetry.</div>\n<p><strong>MEASURING SPREAD</strong></p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>One way to measure the spread of data is to calculate the <strong>range</strong>, maximum minus minimum. What range of cell sizes did each sugar grow? Why is the range often not a useful measure of spread?</li><li>Another method for measuring the spread is the average distance to the mean, called the <strong>mean absolute deviation</strong>. Find the distance each value is to the mean, remember to use absolute value because distances are positive, and find the mean distance. Compare the mean absolute deviation of Sugar W to Sugar P.</li><li>A mean absolute deviation should not be calculated if the data has outliers or is not symmetric. Why?</li><li>When the data is not symmetric or has outliers, the interquartile range (IQR) can be used to measure spread. Compare the IQR of the two sugars. If you need a reminder, read the Math Notes box about calculating IQR at the end of Lesson 11.2.1.</li></ol>\n</section>",
