    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-62\">\n<h2>11-62</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Other: Statistics and Probability / One-Variable Data Displays and Summary Statistics</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Introduces standard deviation as a squared-distance measure of variability and uses it to compare two data sets.</div>\n<p><strong>STANDARD DEVIATION</strong></p>\n<p>In Chapter 6, you learned about residuals, the distance that points are from the line of best fit. In the process of finding the line of best fit, you had to make all the residuals positive because distances are usually positive. You learned that statisticians prefer to make numbers positive by squaring them instead of using the absolute value.</p>\n<p>The standard deviation is another measure of how much variability there is in a data set. <strong>Standard deviation</strong> is the average of all the distances to the mean, after the distances have been made positive by squaring. After finding the average, take the square root of the average so units come out right.</p>\n<p>Without using your graphing calculator, find the standard deviation of each sugar in problem 11-60. Compare the variability, or spread, of the two sugars.</p>\n</section>",
