    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"11-103\">\n<h2>11-103</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Other: Statistics and Probability / One-Variable Data Displays and Summary Statistics</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Compares two one-variable data sets using IQR, standard deviation, histograms, and boxplots; keeps the useful Desmos HW eTool link.</div>\n<p>Duncan is testing two types of memory chips ($W$ and $Z$) for performance and reliability. One test involves a measurement of the maximum electrical current in milliamperes required by the chip when storing and retrieving $14$ different data sets. A lower required current means greater energy efficiency. <a class=\"resource\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/t95llncxzc\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">11-103 HW eTool</a></p>\n<p><strong>Data Set:</strong></p>\n<table class=\"data\"><tr><th></th><th>A</th><th>B</th><th>C</th><th>D</th><th>E</th><th>F</th><th>G</th><th>H</th><th>I</th><th>J</th><th>K</th><th>L</th><th>M</th><th>N</th></tr><tr><td class=\"label\">Chip W</td><td>130</td><td>130</td><td>132</td><td>132</td><td>133</td><td>133</td><td>133</td><td>134</td><td>135</td><td>135</td><td>135</td><td>137</td><td>137</td><td>137</td></tr><tr><td class=\"checksum\" colspan=\"15\">checksum 1873</td></tr><tr><td class=\"label\">Chip Z</td><td>129</td><td>131</td><td>131</td><td>132</td><td>132</td><td>132</td><td>133</td><td>133</td><td>133</td><td>133</td><td>134</td><td>137</td><td>138</td><td>140</td></tr><tr><td class=\"checksum\" colspan=\"15\">checksum 1868</td></tr></table>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li>When Duncan is trying to summarize the data, he finds the IQR for chip $W$ is larger, but the standard deviation for chip $Z$ is larger. Both are measures of spread. How can they be conflicting? Use combination histogram and boxplots in your explanation.</li><li>Which chip should Duncan recommend to the manufacturer? Justify your choice.</li></ol>\n</section>",
