    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"CP08-04\"><h2>CP08-04</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Checkpoint 8</span> LSRL and Residuals</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Students interpret a least-squares regression model, correlation coefficient, and residual in context.</div>\n<p>A team of college students in a Geography class were asked to determine if there is an association between latitude and mean daily temperature of cities in the United States. Latitude is measured in degrees and indicates how far north of the equator the city is. The students gathered data from the Internet and recorded the mean January temperatures of $142$ large cities and each city's latitude. The scatterplot appeared to be reasonably linear, so the students created a least squares regression line.</p>\n<p>The LSRL was $T=125-2.3L$, where $T$ is the mean January temperature, in degrees Fahrenheit, and $L$ is the latitude, in degrees. The correlation coefficient was $r=-0.85$.</p>\n<ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\">\n<li>Describe the association, including an interpretation of the slope and the correlation coefficient in context.</li>\n<li>A city with a latitude of $40$ degrees has a residual of $35$ degrees. Should the city advertise that it is warmer than expected in winter, or that it is a winter wonderland of ice and snow because it is colder than expected in winter?</li>\n<li>What is the actual mean January temperature for the city in part (b)?</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"workspace workspace-lg\"></div>\n</section>",
